    "updated_at": "2014-06-02T18:16:07Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "The problem is really that I'm trying to launch ipython from a nodejs app (node-webkit), perhaps that's just being obtuse and i should switch to something python based  and have easier access to the application machinery :P\n\nBut a big part of my idea is that the deskop shell I'm building shouldn't have to know much about your ipython install beyond how to spawn a process (so mostly just the ipython executable location) and connect to the server.\n\nOn reflection using cmds is not much of a problem/not that much different from what i was thinking of. \nWhat I had in mind was the ability to send() a message to the ipython server process (just a string, like \"port\") and it would output basic information like its currently bound port. But that's just a first idea, there are probably better ways to embed ipython in another app.\n\nFor now I think I can hack it with what you've told me, I'm rather focusing on just making it work at all with minimum amount of new code so I think i am good to go!\n"
  },
